    <a name="research-and-discovery"></a><h2>Research and Discovery</h2>
    <h3>Observation #1: Interviews revealed that the preconceived solution of nested groups failed to satisfy all of our customers business needs.</h3>
    <p>To kick off this project we conducted extensive customer interviews with iAuditor administrators. These interviews revealed that, for small and medium teams, the mental model of templates sharing down and reports sharing up a tree structure worked. However, large organisations had complex sharing needs, which would require constant overriding of any automatic hierarchical sharing.</p>
    <img src="/resources/img/vision/cross-sharing.png" class="responsive" width="100%">
    <h4>Example 1 - Cross Sharing</h4>
    <p>When a template is created at a certain node, but is required to be accessible by everyone on that node level and below. Eg, a template created at node B needs to be accessible to everyone under node B and C as B and C are on the same level.</p>

    {{> spacer size='50'}}

    <img src="/resources/img/vision/mystery-shopper.png" class="responsive" width="100%">
    <h4>Example 2 - Mystery Shopper</h4>
    <p>When an inspection is completed, but the node level directly above shouldn’t see the inspection report. Eg, an inspection is conducted at node D, but node B shouldn't see the inspection report but node A should see it.</p>

    {{> spacer size='50'}}

    <img src="/resources/img/vision/travelling-auditor.png" class="responsive" width="100%">
    <h4>Example 3 - Travelling Auditor</h4>
    <p>If a user is part of multiple groups, and they complete an inspection, how do we determine which route of sharing the completed inspection should take? Eg, a user is part of node D and G, should node B or C see the completed inspection report?</p>

    {{> spacer size='50'}}

    <h3>Observation #2: Our customer base had outgrown the rudimentary user administration and team management tools that iAuditor offered.</h3>
    <p>Internal interviews with staff who assist iAuditor administrators on a daily basis (the support and success teams), in combination with our customer interviews highlighted that administrators lacked basic visibility and management over their users.</p>
    <p>We identified and recorded a large number of jobs to be done (JTBD) that administrators needed to do that were either too difficult or impossible. These included:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Resetting a users password</li>
      <li>Editing a users account details (name, email, timezone, notification settings)</li>
      <li>Viewing a list of all templates and inspections a user had access to</li>
      <li>Viewing a list of all groups a user was part of</li></li>
      <li>Viewing all devices a user is associated with</li>
      <li>Viewing when a user last logged in</li>
    </ul>

    {{> spacer size='50'}}

    <h3>Observation #3 - The sharing pain was actually a symptom of a much larger problem.</h3>
    <p>There existed two main pain points surrounding the task of sharing. Initial setup; and validating that users had correct document access. Our initial plan of automating the sharing process via nested groups only addressed one part of the problem (initial setup). If we released a method to automatically share documents, without fixing the visibility issues, we would dramatically increase the manual complexity of identifying if users had access to the documents they should.</p>
    <p>It was vital that we provided a method for administrators to confirm who had access to what, at the individual level, before we allowed any type of of automated sharing.</p>

