    <a name="outcomes"></a><h2>Outcomes</h2>
    <h3>Our vision made it onto the product roadmap and a second team was assigned to assist in delivering the vision.</h3>
    <p>We successfully secured buy in for Team Management to undertake this project. By focusing initially on user management, Dylan and I afforded ourselves more time to spend exploring other options for simplifying sharing. During my time with the team I saw the delivery of Milestone 1 which you can <a href="/case-study-2/">read more about here</a>.</p>
    <h3>I established a repeatable process that I now adopt in all my projects.</h3>
    <p>This was my first large scale project as a Product Designer. The process that I followed is one that I now employ and continue to tweak with each new project. The process can be broken down into several phases:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Stakeholder analysis:</strong> Conduct external customer and/or internal staff interviews.</li>
      <li><strong>Distil findings:</strong> Identify and document JTBD and/or customer stories.</li>
      <li><strong>Sketch:</strong> Begin rough mocks of deliverables and flows.</li>
      <li><strong>Roadmap breakdown:</strong> Roughy identify, scope and prioritise deliverables for each release.</li>
      <li><strong>Stakeholder buy in:</strong> Pitch the vision; roadmap; and rough mocks to stakeholders to secure project resources.</li>
      <li><strong>Design and implementation:</strong> A conventional cycle of designing; user testing; and refining.</li>
    </ul>
