    <a name="conclusion"></a><h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <h3>I learnt a lot about user research and research methods as a result of this project.</h3>
    <p>Upon starting this project there was a <strong>strongly held preconceived solution</strong> to a very <strong>loosely defined problem</strong>. This was, in itself, the most challenging part of this project. It was imperative that we steered this project away from being solutions led and back to being problem focused.</p>
    <p>While I think we did a great job redirecting the project back to being problem led, I do think that early on we spent to much time trying to make that preconceived solution of nested groups work.</p>
    <h3>This experience reinforced the importance of asking "why?"</h3>
    <p>During the research and discovery phase, I had staff and customers suggesting that the product should do X, Y and Z. Upon further questioning it was almost always revealed that X, Y and Z were simply bandaid solutions to a deeper problem. I was often reminded of the Henry Ford quote "If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said faster horses".</p>
    <h3>I found my voice!</h3>
    <p>At the start of this project I was a reasonably new to Product Design, with little experience interviewing customers and pitching to stakeholders. This project saw my confidence and skills as a Product Designer grow exponentially. This experience helped me find my voice and become the voice for our customers.</p>
